{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17606971","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17606971"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:18:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:18:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15939"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15939","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15939"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8630"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72842"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8630","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8630"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15939"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58312"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"8658"},{"type":"tags","id":"8661"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20667"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20669"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72842","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72842"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring early embryonic development, the neural plate undergoes significant changes to form the neural tube.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the neural folds during primary neurulation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Lateral edges of the neural plate that elevate dorsally","Grooves that form within the notochord","Central region of the neural plate that deepens ventrally","Spaces that develop between adjacent somites","Specialised cells that migrate between ectoderm layers"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring primary neurulation, the \u003Cstrong\u003Elateral edges of the neural plate elevate dorsally\u003C/strong\u003E to form the neural folds. These folds continue to rise and eventually meet and fuse at the dorsal midline to form the neural tube.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGrooves that form within the notochord\u003C/strong\u003E - The notochord induces neural plate formation but does not contain neural folds\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECentral region of the neural plate that deepens ventrally\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes the neural groove, not the neural folds\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESpaces that develop between adjacent somites\u003C/strong\u003E - These are intersomitic clefts, unrelated to neurulation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESpecialised cells that migrate between ectoderm layers\u003C/strong\u003E - This better describes neural crest cells which form after neural tube closure\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENeural fold fusion begins in the cervical region around day 22 and proceeds both cranially and caudally. The anterior neuropore closes by day 25, and the posterior neuropore closes by day 27.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Neural folds are the elevated lateral edges of the neural plate that form during primary neurulation.","Neural fold fusion begins in the cervical region on day 22 and proceeds bidirectionally.","Neural tube closure is complete when the anterior neuropore closes on day 25 and posterior neuropore closes on day 27."],"references":["Sadler TW. Langman\u0027s Medical Embryology: Wolters Kluwer; 2015."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58312"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15939"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58312","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/58312"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-22T09:50:56+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-22T09:51:56+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8630"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72842"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4930"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Nervous System","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-27T10:23:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"13"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4949","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4949"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc23","name":"Embry